Q48: Long-line and industrial-scale commercial fishing in the Pacific near Hawaii have dramatically reduced fish stocks over the past 20 years. The regulation of species such as yellowfin has been sorely lacking. The appearance, and probably the reality is that the management of this fishery has been corrupted and caters to long-line fishers without regard to the actual data which shows a dramatic reduction in the average size and maturity of the yellowfin and other species caught. As someone who has fished in Hawaii for 40 years, and with an education in marine science, it''s clear that a dramatic reduction in catch has occurred in near shore waters out to 30 miles from the coast resulting directly from large scale commercial removal of mature fish stock in the central pacific. If it continues, the tipping point will be reached with the yellowfin stock near Hawaii crashing. AT that point it will be too late to regulate effectively. This tragic lesson has been learned in the Atlantic, we should not repeat it here. Action should be taken now to reduce commercial long-line catch and to eliminate illegal long-liner activity. In addition, industrial scale fishing by other countries should be limited through strictly enforced regulations. Without action now our next generation will not be able to enjoy fishing, and the current economics of fish supply and demand in the Pacific will be changed irreparably.
